In the realm of mobile application development, expertise in programming languages that are compatible with the operating system is crucial. Android app developers typically use either Java or Kotlin, both of which have their own unique characteristics. Java is an object-oriented language that runs on the Java Virtual Machine, boasting a simple syntax, while Kotlin is a concise language that supports functional programming. Conversely, iOS app developers utilize either Swift, a powerful language developed by Apple, or Objective-C, an older language still in use. Swift is a compiled language with a wide range of modern features such as optionals, closures, and generics, making it a popular choice among developers for its high performance. Objective-C, on the other hand, has a more intricate syntax but lacks the modern features of Swift. 
For the Android code snippet below, the programming language used is clearly stated in the text. However, can you identify which programming language is used in the following code snippet? 
```
public class MyActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    @Override
    protected void onStart() {
        super.onStart();
        System.out.println("Hello World!");
    }
}
```
Note that the programming language in question is one of the four mentioned earlier. Good luck!
